 :tx/rationale "UAQ INSIGHT 8: BRAID AS COMPILER — SOURCE IR / MIDDLE IR / TARGET IR. The acquisition function IS a compilation pipeline. Source IR = datom store (65K+ datoms, full knowledge state). Middle IR = ranked propositions (AcquisitionScore-annotated items — tasks, blocks, boundaries — ordered by composite score). Target IR = rendered tokens (ACP projection, budget-constrained, LLM-specific). The compilation passes are: (1) BOUNDARY PASS: evaluate F(S) boundaries → identify gaps → produce impact scores. (2) ROUTING PASS: compute R(t) for tasks → produce task-level AcquisitionScores. (3) CONTEXT PASS: score context blocks → produce block-level AcquisitionScores. (4) MERGE PASS: combine task scores and block scores into one ranked list (middle IR). (5) BUDGET PASS: select top-K items that fit in token budget (target IR). (6) RENDER PASS: format for specific output mode (human, agent, json, tsv). The MIDDLE IR is reusable: same ranked proposition list can be rendered differently for Claude (verbose prose), Codex (structured data), or a human dashboard (graphs). This is the compile-to-prompt paradigm from Session 029 (EPIC t-f5300190, closed as superseded) — but now grounded in the UAQ formalism. The middle IR IS the sorted Vec<(AcquisitionScore, Item)>. No new type needed — it's the natural output of the acquisition function applied to all items. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, ADR-FOUNDATION-019."
